03912nam a22004935i 9780674986275DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20182018mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806749862757 a10.4159/97806749862752doi  a(DE-B1597)501479  a(OCoLC)1027218809  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aKZ1242b.P58 2018eb 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a341.092231 aPitts, Jennifer , eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBoundaries of the International :bLaw and Empire /cJennifer Pitts. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (188 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Empire and International Law -- tOriental Despotism and the Ottoman Empire -- tNations and Empires in Vattel’s World -- tCritical Legal Universalism in the Eighteenth Century -- tThe Rise of Positivism? -- tHistoricism in Victorian International Law -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt is commonly believed that international law originated in relations among European states that respected one another as free and equal. In fact, as Jennifer Pitts shows, international law was forged at least as much through Europeans’ domineering relations with non-European states and empires, leaving a legacy still visible in the unequal structures of today’s international order. Pitts focuses on the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries, the great age of imperial expansion, as European intellectuals and administrators worked to establish and justify laws to govern emerging relationships with non-Europeans. Relying on military and commercial dominance, European powers dictated their own terms on the basis of their own norms and interests. Despite claims that the law of nations was a universal system rooted in the values of equality and reciprocity, the laws that came to govern the world were parochial and deeply entangled in imperialism. Legal authorities, including Emer de Vattel, John Westlake, and Henry Wheaton, were key figures in these developments. But ordinary diplomats, colonial administrators, and journalists played their part too, as did some of the greatest political thinkers of the time, among them Montesquieu and John Stuart Mill. Against this growing consensus, however, dissident voices as prominent as Edmund Burke insisted that European states had extensive legal obligations abroad that ought not to be ignored. These critics, Pitts shows, provide valuable resources for scrutiny of the political, economic, and legal inequalities that continue to afflict global affairs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aInternational lawxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060662140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067498627540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674986275423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674986275.jpg  a978-3-11-060662-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles